Rebecca,

As it turns out, the C++ interface to allow working with liquid/vapor 
equations of state was not finished.  Now it is, at least for water.  
Now there is a C++ class Water, so you can do things like this:

#include &lt;cantera/PureFluid.h&gt;

main() {
    Water w;
    w.setState_TP(300.0, OneAtm);
    double s1 = w.entropy_mass();
    w.setState_SP(s1, 8.0*OneAtm);
    cout &lt;&lt; w.temperature() &lt;&lt; endl;
    ...
    etc.
    ...
}

I have also added an example of an open Rankine cycle in C++.  All you 
need to do is &quot;cvs update&quot;, then build everything and re-install. The 
new example will appear in the demos folder in the installation 
directory. Oh, and I fixed the include statement for 
&quot;../../ext/tpx/...&quot;.  Now this include is in the implementation file, 
not the header, so it is not needed for application programs. Let me 
know if you encounter any problems.

Dave


